<!-- ABOUT AVALANCHES -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>About Avalanches</h2>
  <p>
    An avalanche is a sudden and rapid sliding of a mass of snow, ice, and rock down a mountain slope.
    Avalanches are common in high-altitude regions like the Himalayas (Jammu & Kashmir, Himachal Pradesh, Uttarakhand).
  </p>
  <p>
    They can bury roads, houses, and people within seconds, making awareness and preparedness very important.
  </p>
</article>

<!-- CAUSES & WARNING SIGNS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Causes & Warning Signs</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Heavy snowfall and rapid snow accumulation.</li>
    <li>Sudden temperature rise causing snow to melt and loosen.</li>
    <li>Steep slopes with unstable snow layers.</li>
    <li>Loud sounds, explosives, or human movement on risky slopes.</li>
    <li>New cracks in the snow or a ‚Äúwhumpf‚Äù sound underfoot.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- PREPAREDNESS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Preparedness Before Visiting Avalanche Areas</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Check avalanche forecasts and weather conditions.</li>
    <li>Carry safety gear: beacon, shovel, probe, rope, first-aid kit.</li>
    <li>Travel with trained guides or experienced groups.</li>
    <li>Avoid steep slopes and cornices during heavy snow or thawing periods.</li>
    <li>Attend basic mountain safety and rescue training.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- DOs & DON'Ts -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Do‚Äôs & Don‚Äôts During Avalanche Risk</h2>

  <h3>‚úî Do‚Äôs</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Follow local authority and mountain patrol instructions.</li>
    <li>Use marked routes and trails only.</li>
    <li>Keep enough distance between group members while walking.</li>
    <li>Wear bright clothing for visibility.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>‚ùå Don‚Äôts</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Do NOT walk or ski on steep slopes after heavy snowfall.</li>
    <li>Do NOT ignore warning boards or closed zones.</li>
    <li>Do NOT stop under overhanging snow or cornices.</li>
    <li>Do NOT shout or make loud noises in high-risk zones.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- HOW TO REACT IF CAUGHT -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>What To Do If Caught in an Avalanche</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Move sideways to the avalanche path if possible.</li>
    <li>Try to grab onto a tree, rock, or fixed object.</li>
    <li>Use swimming motions to stay near the surface of the snow.</li>
    <li>Before being buried, try to create an air pocket in front of your face.</li>
    <li>Once stopped, stay calm and conserve energy; shout only if rescuers are close.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- HELPING OTHERS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>How to Help Others After an Avalanche</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Immediately alert local rescue teams or emergency services.</li>
    <li>Look for visible equipment, clothing, or hands on the snow surface.</li>
    <li>Use avalanche beacons, probes, and shovels to locate buried persons.</li>
    <li>Provide first-aid and keep rescued people warm.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

